		<pb n="1"/>
          <p rend="align(center)"><placeName>Baltimore</placeName> <date>January 23<hi rend="sup">rd</hi> 1848</date></p>
          <p>Dear Friend <addressee>Isaac&#59;</addressee></p>
          <p rend="indent(2)">&#39;tis a very long time since I have written<lb/> to you&#44; and you care very little about it I dare say for the<lb/> letters of an old married woman possess very little<lb/> interest to young unmarried <hi rend="underline">gents</hi>&#44; however full of human<lb/> frailty and the vanity all predominant in woman I<lb/> for truth send you another one of my scrawls&#44; but fear me<lb/> &#39;twill meet the same treatment as the last&#8212;in the first<lb/> place my rapience<add>&#63;</add>&#44; I imagine you are unlike those sun&#45;<lb/>shine friends which sheds a &#39;lustre on our way when we are<lb/> prosperous and adds to the darkness when adversity<lb/> surrounds us&#8212;therefore I am induced to make known our<lb/> deplorable situation&#8212;you know my husband is striving in<lb/> <placeName>New York</placeName> to get up a school&#44; and that he has met with<lb/> little encouragement&#44; ten scholars is all he has not enough<lb/> to pay his expenses there&#44; and I am left with my family<lb/> without the means of support&#44; I have wished and tried<lb/> to procure some boarders but I cannot hear of any who<lb/> care about <sic>cosher</sic> living and as to christians I fear<lb/> they would not be satisfied with our mode of living now<lb/> I wish you to tell me <hi rend="underline">candidly</hi> what you think will<lb/> be the result of <persName>Eleaser&#39;s</persName> undertaking is there a prospect<lb/> of an increase from any other quarter than the people<lb/> of <placeName>New York</placeName>&#44; all such matters take time but unfortunately<lb/> we are so poor that time cannot be spared in an&#45;<lb/>ticipation. I think perhaps were he to ask less price</p>
		<pb n="2"/>
          <p>for younger children he might do better&#95;do dear <persName>Isaac</persName><lb/> interest yourself for us and if you think there is a better<lb/> opening in your city or elsewhere let us know and if<lb/> a boarding house would succeed in either place. I cannot but believe that our merciful Father will not<lb/> suffer those to want who so <sic>confidantly</sic> depend in<lb/> his mercy to relieve their necessities and actively strive<lb/> with all their energies to live&#8212;I regret my inability<lb/> at present to pay you for those two prayer books&#44; but<lb/> hope to do so at some future day&#44; and also that I<lb/> cannot afford to be any longer a subscriber to the<lb/> publication society&#8212;when I can renew it I will let you<lb/> know&#8212;should any one come this way who wishes to<lb/> live <sic>cosher</sic> whilst <sic>her</sic> I <sic>shold</sic> be glad to have them<lb/> stop with us&#8212;your Cousin <persName>Myer</persName> reports he was engaged<lb/> to me and that I am his Cousin&#44; so of course am yours<lb/> he has quite a pretty daughter I am told&#8212;I need not<lb/> <sic>as</sic> you not to expose the contents of this as I well<lb/> know you will only do that which will be right&#8212;</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">God bless and send you better health and better<lb/> fortune than your poor friend</p>
          <p rend="indent(11)"><persName role="author">A. Block</persName></p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">remembrance to all friends&#8212;love <sic>&#8220;</sic>to my Aunt<lb/> <persName>Mark&#39;s</persName> and A new house and offer my congratulations<lb/> to them&#8212;I just recollected that I told <persName>Rosalie</persName><lb/> to pay you for those books did she do<lb/> so&#63;</p>
     <pb n="3"/>
          <p><addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
